For test case 5 only, there is not a newline at the end of the input. This causes certain implementations of taking input to fail. For example, the following code works on all test cases but 5 because of the malformed input.

l=[i[:-1]for i in open(0)]
print(max(l,key=lambda x:l.count(x)))

Once that minor issue is addressed, this problem is great!
Great puzzle, +1 upvote, I like your code golf solution haha

Cases
* Please add a pair of cases where each word occurs exactly once.

* Currently the answer is the first word for 3 out of 4 tests and 3 out of 4 validators. Please revise/add cases to ensure this outcome occurs in no more than half of the cases (after the first point has been followed up).

Just as an example, assuming there are 4 words a, b, c and d (using letters for simplicity only) and the order of their first appearance is a < b < c < d, and fa, fb, fc, fd represent their respective frequencies, you may consider to add situations such as:
   • fa < fb < fc < fd (answer is d)
   • fa < fb < fc = fd (answer is c)
   • fa < fb = fc = fd (answer is b)
   • fa < fb = fc < fd (answer is d)
etc.

Thanks.
